Pour 300ml cold salted @water{300%ml}(per 2P) into a #medium pot{} with a tight-fitting
lid.

Stir in the @rice{150%g} and half the @ground turmeric{1/2%sachet} and bring to the
boil.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium, cover with the #lid{} and cook for
~{10%minutes}.

Remove the #pot{} from the heat and keep covered for another ~{10%minutes} or
until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced).

Shake the @coconut milk{1%pack} to dissolve any lumps.

Place a #pan{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Fry the onion until softened, stirring occasionally, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Remove the skin from the @salmon{200%g}. Tilt the blade towards the skin to avoid
removing too much flesh. Slide the blade along the length of the fillet, holding
the skin firmly.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

Add @mustard{1%sachet}, coconut milk and half the @dried chilli flakes{1%sachet}
(use less if you don't like spice) to the pan. Mix well to combine.

Stir in the @baby spinach{60%g} and @peas{120%g}. Bring to a boil.

Taste and season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Place the fish on the stew. Sprinkle the remaining @ground turmeric{1/2%sachet}
over the top.

Cover and simmer until the fish is cooked, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Fish is cooked when opaque in the middle. Once cooked, add a splash
> of water if you feel it's too thick.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and divide between plates.

Top with the coconut stew and salmon.

Garnish with as many of the remaining @?dried chilli flakes{1%sachet} as you'd like!